An asthma attack is the sudden worsening of asthma symptoms caused by the tightening of muscles around the airways. During the asthma attack, the lining of the airways becomes swollen and thicker mucus, more than normal, is produced.The visible symptoms are difficulty in breathing, wheezing, coughing, shortness of breath and difficulty performing normal daily activities. Moreover, one can present with signs such as rapid breathing, chest tightness and tightened neck and chest muscles, called retractions.A severe asthma attack can lead to feelings of anxiety or panic, difficulty in talking and pale sweaty face with blue lips or fingernails.Asthma attack can happen anytime and at any place. The attack can start suddenly or slowly. It can be mild or severe. Sometimes a mild attack will seem to go away, but will come back a few hours later, and the second attack turns out worse than the first.It is important to recognise and treat even mild symptoms of an asthma attack to help you prevent severe episodes and keep asthma under control. Severe attack needs immediate medical intervention to prevent morbidity and even death.First aid tips for asthma attack Help the patient into a position of greatest comfort. Usually this is sitting upright while leaning forward. Be calm and reassuring. Loosen tight or restrictive clothing. Encourage the person to breathe slowly and deeply. If the person has asthma medication, such as reliever inhaler, help the patient take it. Get them to take one or two puffs of their inhaler every two minutes with maximum of 10 puffs. If the patient does not have any medication encourage him/her to continue breathing slowly and deeply whilst taking him/her to the nearest healthcare centre.